00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:46.339
involved with bigger communities and, um, uh, that are more even global, you know, like

00:17:46.339 --> 00:17:47.979
even global kinds of communities.

00:17:47.979 --> 00:17:59.500
I think that something that I noticed makes a difference is, um, a sense that when I bring

00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:07.699
my time, my knowledge, my energy, it comes and it, it really, it really multiplies.

00:18:07.699 --> 00:18:13.540
Like it really, um, like I, I, but I do have to bring myself, I have to bring myself and

00:18:13.540 --> 00:18:21.140
my, uh, what I know now and, uh, what I'm interested in and like, uh, it takes energy

00:18:21.140 --> 00:18:22.140
and effort.

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:27.459
I mean, I know you're very familiar, you've been spending so much effort and work on this

00:18:27.459 --> 00:18:28.459
conference, right?

00:18:28.459 --> 00:18:29.459
It's so much work.

00:18:29.459 --> 00:18:37.339
It's so, you know, it's so much work and it, so you come and you bring that, but then it,

00:18:37.339 --> 00:18:43.819
um, you also like, that's, then everyone else does that to some level too.

00:18:43.819 --> 00:18:48.500
And then what you have there together is, uh, like multiplied.

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:53.900
And I mean, this is kind of, um, I don't know, I don't know about this analogy or what you'll

00:18:53.900 --> 00:19:00.300
think about this analogy, but it's like, it's like, um, building friendships really because

00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:04.500
you know, in your, maybe in your non data science life, you're like, oh, I went to work

00:19:04.500 --> 00:19:07.819
and I'm tired.

00:19:07.819 --> 00:19:11.859
And yes, I was going to go to dinner with my friend, but I'm very tired.

00:19:11.859 --> 00:19:14.500
And I'm like, oh, I'm, I can't come tonight.

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:18.900
You know, it's like, I'm just going to stay home and scroll on my phone and eat at home

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:24.420
and, and it feels easier and it feels more like, um, relaxing maybe.

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:26.859
Um, and it's so easy.

00:19:26.859 --> 00:19:32.020
It's so easy to say like, not tonight, not tonight, I'm not going to come and meet you.

00:19:32.020 --> 00:19:39.579
But the, it's like, if you do go and to have the dinner with the friend, um, like, yes,

00:19:39.579 --> 00:19:45.420
you maybe had to put your shoes back on and put, you know, maybe you decided to put lipstick

00:19:45.420 --> 00:19:48.180
back on or you're like, oh, okay, I'm going to do it.

00:19:48.180 --> 00:19:49.180
I'm going to go out.

00:19:49.180 --> 00:19:54.459
I'm going to see this friend, but you, that, then that, that friend has done it too.

00:19:54.459 --> 00:19:57.380
And then together you like build in with each other.

00:19:57.380 --> 00:20:06.459
And I think that the ingredients, it's like, um, it, it really does take, it like takes

00:20:06.459 --> 00:20:07.459
energy and effort.

00:20:07.459 --> 00:20:14.140
Um, but then when you're there, it's like the other person also brought their energy

00:20:14.140 --> 00:20:15.140
and effort.

00:20:15.140 --> 00:20:20.420
And then it's like, instead of both of you having less, both of you have more, both of

00:20:20.420 --> 00:20:21.420
you have more.

00:20:21.420 --> 00:20:26.780
And I, when I think about, um, when I think about open source communities, I like, I think

00:20:26.780 --> 00:20:32.459
that's an analogy that works because it's, it, it, it took something for you to show

00:20:32.459 --> 00:20:33.459
up.

00:20:33.459 --> 00:20:35.380
I mean, it took a lot for you to show up right here.

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:37.380
It took something for me to get here.

00:20:37.380 --> 00:20:38.380
Right.

00:20:38.380 --> 00:20:44.099
But, um, when we, it's not like we both now have less, it's like now this whole, this

00:20:44.099 --> 00:20:49.099
whole, everyone who's here at PyCon Colombia, like we all have more.

00:20:49.099 --> 00:20:50.099
So that's what I think.

00:20:50.099 --> 00:20:51.099
I don't know.

00:20:51.099 --> 00:20:52.099
What do you think about that analogy?

00:20:52.099 --> 00:20:56.339
I love it because we need to build friendships and we need to build community.

00:20:56.339 --> 00:21:02.260
And usually I try to imagine, like, I love nature and I try to imagine that we are different

00:21:02.260 --> 00:21:04.219
type of trees.

00:21:04.219 --> 00:21:09.660
So we are kind of taking care of the tree or the plant with flowers, with like butterflies

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:10.660
or not.

00:21:10.660 --> 00:21:15.780
We like, like we can imagine that my longest friendship that is like 18 years ago, like

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:19.300
I can imagine that like a big, big and huge tree.

00:21:19.300 --> 00:21:20.300
Yeah.

00:21:20.619 --> 00:21:25.380
We know how we work with each other, but we, we, we grow together, that tree, right?

00:21:25.380 --> 00:21:27.180
So community is like a forest.

00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:30.339
You know, like many things are happening, they're growing there.

00:21:30.339 --> 00:21:31.420
We have roots.

00:21:31.420 --> 00:21:35.060
We leave seeds because we cannot be in the community forever.

00:21:35.060 --> 00:21:36.060
Yeah.

00:21:36.060 --> 00:21:37.060
Yeah.

00:21:37.060 --> 00:21:40.660
So that is kind of something that we are building and that is building community and I agree

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:41.660
with your analogy.

00:21:41.660 --> 00:21:42.660
I like it.

00:21:42.660 --> 00:21:43.660
Thank you so much.

00:21:43.660 --> 00:21:44.660
Thank you.

00:21:44.660 --> 00:21:45.660
So for closing.

00:21:45.660 --> 00:21:46.660
Right.

00:21:46.660 --> 00:21:49.660
So you, I can see you as a role model, right?

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:56.140
I would like you to share with more girls and women that may see this interview because

00:21:56.140 --> 00:22:01.020
you have been loud, vocal advocate for women in data science.

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:02.020
Yeah.

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:03.660
Like what would you recommend to them?

00:22:03.660 --> 00:22:09.060
Like what would be a message for them to keep pursuing that leadership and to be leaders

00:22:09.060 --> 00:22:14.459
and to be part of that science area and keep doing work with this technology?

00:22:14.459 --> 00:22:15.459
Yeah.

00:22:15.540 --> 00:22:21.739
So I'm going to say something kind of specific, actually kind of specific.

00:22:21.739 --> 00:22:25.180
And I don't know that everyone would agree with what I'm about to say, but this is my,

00:22:25.180 --> 00:22:26.660
this is something I think I've observed.

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:35.140
So I think, you know, girls are socialized to really like to take care of other people,

00:22:35.140 --> 00:22:39.500
to be nurturing, to be, to value connection.

00:22:39.500 --> 00:22:41.880
And so we grow up that way often.

00:22:41.880 --> 00:22:51.800
And so like often, often women are actually really good at building connection, are really

00:22:51.800 --> 00:22:59.439
good at that connect, like understanding what someone needs and kind of helping them to

00:22:59.439 --> 00:23:00.439
have it.

00:23:00.439 --> 00:23:08.520
And how that can play out in technical careers is that like, if you're going to get really

00:23:08.520 --> 00:23:15.119
concrete, like often women are identified as like, Ooh, that person would be so good

00:23:15.119 --> 00:23:16.400
as a manager.

00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:19.479
You know, like that person would be so good.

00:23:19.479 --> 00:23:22.280
She's so good with people.

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:27.839
We should have her start to do maybe more like, Oh, we can have her do like the less

00:23:27.839 --> 00:23:31.040
technical work because she's very good at it.

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:36.959
And then it's like, Oh, well, she's, she's less technical, you know, like, is she so

00:23:36.959 --> 00:23:37.959
technical?

00:23:37.959 --> 00:23:49.199
So I think I, an advice I have is to, um, to not step into roles that are explicitly

00:23:49.199 --> 00:23:59.199
about, um, the quote, less technical work before you really want to, or before you're

00:23:59.199 --> 00:24:00.199
really ready.

00:24:00.199 --> 00:24:01.680
I like, I think I do.

00:24:01.680 --> 00:24:02.680
I have advice.

00:24:02.680 --> 00:24:10.439
Like, I think it's a little, a little more dangerous for a woman to, um, maybe stop being

00:24:10.439 --> 00:24:13.880
hands on with coding work too early.

00:24:13.880 --> 00:24:20.520
Like maybe it's a little, it's a bit, a little bit risky because then you end up, um, uh,

00:24:20.520 --> 00:24:27.000
spending more of your time doing maybe, uh, organizational work and yes, yes, yes.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:29.160
You would send up spending more time on that.

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:34.719
And then in the longterm, it can be a little limiting to your career options.

00:24:34.719 --> 00:24:39.000
Now I think that work is super valuable.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:45.959
I'm not saying it's not important work, but I think, I think if I had advice for especially

00:24:45.959 --> 00:24:54.719
early career women, it would be, um, it would be, if you, if you like technical work, if

00:24:54.719 --> 00:25:06.199
you like data science, coding, um, be, stay on a track that is a more, a more traditional

00:25:06.199 --> 00:25:13.560
technical track for like a little longer, maybe like be, don't too early kind of go

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:19.760
to these roles that are like, um, I don't know, I don't know, like, like manager or,

00:25:20.319 --> 00:25:27.280
um, maybe product manager or DevRel, you know, like, like just be, just be thoughtful, be aware

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:34.560
that, um, depending on how people perceive you, like, like you might want to wait a little bit

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:36.319
to make some kind of those choices.

00:25:36.319 --> 00:25:41.119
And that I want to emphasize is not because I think that work is, is not important.

00:25:41.119 --> 00:25:43.119
It 100% is important.

00:25:43.119 --> 00:25:46.239
We have to have people doing DevRel.

00:25:46.239 --> 00:25:49.599
We have to have people who are the managers of our teams.

00:25:49.599 --> 00:25:51.280
You know, I am now a manager, right?

00:25:51.280 --> 00:25:58.160
But I actually was nervous about stepping into this, like, oh, she's less technical

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:01.439
kind of roles because of what it means for the long-term.

00:26:01.439 --> 00:26:08.319
Like, I think it can provide, it can be, it can limit your long-term options by going

00:26:08.319 --> 00:26:10.959
out of the technical role too early.

00:26:10.959 --> 00:26:17.520
So I know that's very concrete kind of like specific kind of career advice, but I, um,

00:26:17.520 --> 00:26:20.400
I base this on, I feel like what I observed happened.

00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:26.160
And it is true that you end up people who are like raised as girls and adult and then

00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:32.319
now young women or adult women, like we're, we, we are, we tend to be, um, very good at

00:26:32.319 --> 00:26:33.199
some of these skills.

00:26:33.199 --> 00:26:37.119
And so people are like, ah, come, come do this thing, come do this thing.

00:26:37.839 --> 00:26:44.079
And it's like, well, maybe, maybe wait, maybe wait a few years, maybe wait a few years.

00:26:44.079 --> 00:26:51.920
So, because I do think that there's, um, it's really exciting to see women, uh, step

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:56.560
into roles that are really aligned with their interests.

00:26:56.560 --> 00:27:00.640
And I would just want people like, I want, I, you know, I want men and women, but I,

00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:10.479
including women, like I want women to be able to, um, uh, see roles that they have as like

00:27:10.479 --> 00:27:15.280
the fit for them, you know, as like, ah, yes, this is what I want to be doing.

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:20.079
And so keeping your options open, I think can be, um, a really good idea.

